    <h1>Help</h1>

    <h2>What's the point?</h2>

    <p>The Most Dangerous Writing App is designed to shut down your inner editor and get you into a state of flow. If you stop typing for more than five seconds, all progress will be lost.</p>

    <p>Because 'tis better to have written and lost, than never to have written at all.</p>

    <h2>Word on the street?</h2>

    {{ quote("Sadistic [and] brutal.", "WIRED", "https://www.wired.com/2016/03/sadistic-writing-app-deletes-work-stop-typing/") }}

    {{ quote("<a href='https://twitter.com/maebert'>@maebert</a> has created the writer&#39;s nightmare machine.", "@danhklein", "https://twitter.com/danhklein/status/704701084908978176") }}

    {{ quote("I am panicking just reading the description, which should count as a ringing endorsement.", "Some Guy on Metafilter", "http://www.metafilter.com/157549/The-Most-Frustrating-Writing-Webpage#6422455") }}

    <h2>Can anybody read what I wrote?</h2>

    <p>No, all your writing will be private. If you're not logged in or disabled autosave in your profile, nothing will be stored on any server at all.</p>

    <h2>Who made this?</h2>

    <p><i class="icon-mdwa"></i> <abbr title="The Most Dangerous Writing App">MDWA</abbr> was written by <a href="https://www.twitter.com/maebert" target="_blank" title="Manuel Ebert">Manuel Ebert</a>. The first version was written over two glasses of wine and is <a title="MDWA on Github" target="_blank" href="https://www.github.com/maebert/themostdangerouswritingapp"><i class="icon-github"></i>open source</a>.</p>


